<h3 id="sec-1">The Export Template</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-1">

<p>I did not like the defaults when I exported my html files for my blog. I am in the process of customizing my html export.
</p>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-1-1" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-1-1">M-x Customize</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-1-1">

<p>I used emacspeak's customization facility. Curiously, I had to first export an html file before I could find all the org options. I typed "org" into the search box and got a boat load of settings. I was able to turn the preamble off, but some of the other settings were problematic. I don't know yet where these values are stored.
</p></div>

</div>

<div id="outline-container-1-2" class="outline-4">
<h4 id="sec-1-2">Using In-buffer Settings</h4>
<div class="outline-text-4" id="text-1-2">

<p>Org has in-buffer settings. For a list, see [[]].
 To get some of these placed in a file, press:
C-c C-e t
All the words following "#+" are in all upper case characters. Notice the inserted spaces.
I changed the values I wanted to change and then pressed
Cc Cc
to restart org mode so that these lines take effect.
</p>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-1-2-1" class="outline-5">
<h5 id="sec-1-2-1">A File Makes This Easier Still</h5>
<div class="outline-text-5" id="text-1-2-1">

<p>As exciting as this list is, it gets better. zi saved my favorite settings in a file. Then I typed:
and all my settings appeared. I pressed:
Cc C-c
My settings are active, my cursor is placed at a blank line and I have a file I can fill with a new blog entry.
**Note**: Any file name will work.o
</p>
</div>
